AWS scalability , high availability  & load balancing 

Scalability - the ability of a system to grow and shrink based on capacity as workload increase /decreases

2 types of scalability : 
- Vertical scalability - boost the power of a single machine -> more cpu , memory, etc
- Horizontal scalability - add more machines spreading the load across different servers → * elasticity provision up / down when needed *

Scalability linked to High availability 

Vertical Scaling - associated with non distributed systems 

→ increasing the size of a single instance
→ I.e app runs on t2.micro - scale up - t2.large 
→ you just scaled vertically 
→ very common for non distributed systems like a database , ads , elastiCache
→ limit on how much vertical scaling is mostly due to a hardware limit 


Horizontal Scaling - associated with distributed systems - MORE INSTANCES = Resilience +high availability 
→ increasing the number of instances/ systems that your application is running on 
→ If you need to handle - more load you add more instances 
→implies distributed system 
→ common for web app / modern apps 
→ easy to horizontally scale due to cloud offerings like amazon EC2 

Can automate this with auto scaling groups 
No single point of failure as there are multiple instances available 


What is High Availability ?

→ ensures minimal downtime and continuous operation 
→ you run your application on at least 2 avalablity zones ( data centres)  in order to provide resilience 
→ if one availability zone fails , the other keep the service / app running 
→ Reduces single point of failure + resilience 

High availability can be passive 
- Passive high availability means the backup aren’t operational during normal operation hours 
- ( multi relational database ) RDS multi AZ  a standby database is kept in another availability  zone 
- Doesn’t handle traffic and is on standby 
- If primary fails then this one takes over 


What does High availability of EC2 look like ?

Virtual scaling = increase instance size up and down - RAM , CPU , etc 

Horizontal scaling = increasing the number of instances - out and in 
- Auto scaling group - lets you add / remove instances 
- Load balancer - sits infront of EC2 - directs traffic and distributes to the right instance  


High availability ( multi AZ’s ) = run instances of the same app across multiple availability zones 
- Auto scaling group multi AZ - adds / removes instances within the multi AZ’s 
- Load balancer multi AZ - directs and manages traffic across the multi AZ instances 


What is a load balancer ?
 
→ Type of service that distributes incoming requests and traffic downstream to the healthy EC2 instances 
- Load balancer upstream and EC2 instances downstream 
- AWS has service called Elastic load balancer that is their own managed service 
 
Application Load balancer ( load balancer ) can act as a reverse proxy as it handles incoming requests and forwards them to EC2 instances 

 Remember "reverse proxys" = sits infront of servers to filter + route client requests to backend servers ( instances )


Why use a load balancer ?

- Spreads load downstream across multiple instances like EC2’s
- Provides a single DNS endpoint for your app
- Handles failure of instances 
- Conducts health checks on your instances ( I.e EC2 )
- Terminates SSL - handed the decryption of encrypted traffic - instead of backend services doing it 
- Manages HTTP / HTTPS for your sites 
- Enforces session stickiness using cookies - user keeps getting sent to the same instance in their session ( Continuity )
- High availablity across zones 
- Seperates public traffic from private traffic 


Why use an Elastic load balancer ?

Elastic load balancer is a managed load balancer where AWS guarantees it will be working , take care of maintenance + provide config knobs 
- Personal load balancer costs less but more work 
- Integrated with other AWS services 
- Load balancer can be set up as internal (private) or (external) ELB


ELB is the umbrella AWS service and under it comes : 

 → Application lower balancer - ALB  → HTTP , HTTPS , Websocket  

 → Network lower balancer- NLB  → TCP , (secure) TCP , TLS , UDP

 → Classic load balancer  CLB  →HTTP HTTP, TCP , (secure)TCP , SSL 

 →Gateway load balancer - GWLB  → operates at layer 3 (network) ip protocol 



Health checks 

Health checks are crucial for load balancers + consistently check health of instance (stop sending traffic) = good user experience 
→ they let the elastic load balancer of choice know if the instance they are routing traffic to is healthy and available to reply to requests 
→ Health check is done on port and a route ( /health is common )

= if the response is not 200 (OK) , then instance is unhealthy 

i.e Elastic load balancer  → send a request soon HTTP through port 4567  → EC2 instance 
= if return 200 (OK) then healthy 


What are Load Balancer Security groups ?

User  → HTTP/S from anywhere  → Load balancer  → HTTP restricted to Load balancer  → EC2 

Security groups allow your load balancer to accept 
→ TCP traffic on port 80 ( for  HTTP ) 
→ TCP traffic on port 443 ( for HTTPS ) traffic
= your allowing the load balancer to receive both unencrypted and encrypted web traffic 

= once ELB receives traffic it routes it to the backend instances according to the application security group ( allow traffic only from Load Balancer )

application security group -> allows for TCP traffic on port 80 for HTTP from a specific source so only the load balancer can route traffic to it 


Application load balancers in depth ?

- Layer 7 HTTP
- Load balancing to multiple HTTP applications across machines / servers ( target groups )            = collection of resources like EC2’s
- Load balancing to multiple applications on the same machine ( containers 
- ALB can route based on hostname in URL 
- Can route requests / traffic to different target groups based on URL paths 
- Can route on query stringer / headers 
- Can route to MULTIPLE TARGET GROUPS 

- ALB’s are ideal for micro services and container based apps like - ECS , docker
- ALB have port mapping which is great for ECS ( containers ) avoiding the need for multiple clastic load balancers 


Traffic → ALB -> ECS cluster → ECS service ( define what tasks are run) -> EC2 instance → (grouped by target groups) Tasks / containers 
                                                                                                   ECS agent 



Application load balancer then uses the target groups to figure out which where to route the right traffic to the right Tasks / containers  
- ALB has health check as part of it constantly checking health of tasks / containers 


Target Groups ?

Target groups are resources/ tasks that are grouped together that are the end destination of the traffic from the ALB 
Typically each target group is associated with a certain service application = scaling diffrent parts of app independently = good for micro services + docker 

Target groups can be things like - containers , Lambda functions ( HTTP requests translated into JSON events ) etc 
 ALB can route to multiple target groups 


IP addresses with application load balancers ?
1. When ALB created AWS gives it a fixed DNS name like “xxx.region.elb.amazonaws.com”
2. Users the send a request  to the ALB DNS name /  “hostname” ( shortened version of DNS name )
3. ALB receives request
4. ALB then forwards the request to one of your EC2 instances based on TARGET GROUPS AND RULES 

Client IP → Connection terminated → ALB forwards to EC2 instance 
                          At ALB

- EC2 instance sees Private IP &  doesn’t see real client IP  rom load balancer 

- But ALB passes the real client info inside headers =

X-Forwarded-For → contains the real client IP
X-Forwarded-Port → shows the original port used
X-Forwarded-Proto → shows whether the request was HTTP or HTTPS
 

BONUS : REVERSE PROXY = server that lists between client devices and backend services like Load balancing  , SSL , caching 

* SSL termination so that ALB handles encryption to decrypt HTTPS traffic before it hits EC2 *


Network load balancer 

 → operates at layer 4 of OSI model ( transport layer ) - 
- Forwards TCP and UDP traffic to you instances - routes that raw traffic without getting involved in layer 7
- Build for millions for requests 
- Less latency that ALB 
- Used for extreme performance of TCP or UDP traffic 

* → NLB uses one static IP in each availability zone you enable 
 → If you want the NLB IP to stay fixed you can assign as elastic IP address
= means your load balancers external IP Is stable and reusable - useful for whitelisting ( trusted entities ) 


Use case : high traffic , low latency = gaming , real time trading , load balancing no HTTP traffic like Database


Network load balancer handling TCP traffic at Layer 4 ?

1  → Client connects to NLB IP address through IP/DNS name 
2  →  client initiates TCP connect with NLB IP  
3  → NLB applies rules and route TCP traffic to backend instance 
4  → Instance process the connect and request + sends back response to NLB  
5 →  NLB sends response to client 

TCP connection but it can be a HTTP request  →  NBL doesn’t dig just reads IP 


Sticky sessions - session affinity 

= Once client connect to backend service (I.e instance) , the client keeps getting sent to that server for the duration of the session 

- This partically helpful when dealing with shopping carts / logged into app 
- Load balancer uses a cookie or client IP based rule to do this 
- ALB and CLB are the best for this 

→ However enabling stickiness might imbalance the load over the EC2 instances 


SSL/TSL certificates → Allows traffic between your client and Load balancer to be encrypted in traffic ( in flight encryption ) 

- SSL = secure socket layer used to encrypt connections 
- TSL = Trasport layer security is the newer version 
= mainly TSL certificates are used but SSL referred to 

SSL/TSL encrypt and then SSL termination happens at the load balancer → it decrypts and sends the plain data to instance 

* SSL/TSL certificates provided by certificate authorities like GoDaddy + can expire and need renewing 


Load balancer for SSL/TSL ?

Load balancer provides TSL/SSL certificate at the “handshake” to the client to verify the load balancers identity + sets up secure encrypted connection + trust
- Load balancer uses X.509 certificates ( SSL/TSL certificate )
- Can manage certificates with AWS CERTIFICATE MANAGER
- Can also upload your own certificates 

→ on the HTTP listener (door) of the Load balancer 
- You must specify a default certificate 
- You can add optional list of certificates to support multiple domains 
- Able to specify a security policy to support older versions of SSL / TSL 

** Clients can use SNI ( server name indication ) to specify the hostname they reach 
- This is needed if your hosting multiple websites/domains on the same backend server 
* SNI allows the load balancer to present the right certificate depending on the domain the client is requesting.

→ requires the client to indicate the hostname of the target server in the initial SSL handshake **


ELASTIC LOAD BALANCERS - SSL certificates ?

Application lower balancer → supports a multiple listeners (HTTP etc) , with multiple SSL certificates 
- Uses Server name indication (SNI) to make it work 

Network load balancer →  support multiple listeners (HTTP etc) , with multiple SSL certificates 
- Uses server name indication to do this (SNI)

Classic Load balancer →  supports only one SSL certificate 
→  must use multiple CLB’s if you have multiple hostnames/domains on the target server with multiple SSL certificates 



Connection draining && deregistration Delay ?         ** can scale down or set to 0 to cut off connection instantly
  
This is when a backend isntance is deemed to be unhealthy or is stop due to scalling down               
→ it lets existing traffic / in flight requests finish before eventually instance is gracefully stopped          
→  from that point new connects / traffic is only routed to the healthy existing backend instances 

= no abrupt stop/experience for users  


Dereregistration delay = APPLICATION LOAD BALANCER + NETWORK LOAD BALANCER 
Connection delay = CLASSIC LOAD BALANCER 


What is an Auto scaling group  ( ASG ) ? 

Service on AWS where the goal is to: 
- Scale out ( add EC2 instances ) to match increase work load 
- Scale in ( remove EC2 instances ) to match decrease work load 
- Ensure we have a minimum and maximum available EC2 instances running for our app
- Automatically register new EC2 instances to a load balancer 
- Recreate an EC2 instance in case the previous one is terminate ( due to being unhealthy )

→   Auto scaling groups are free you just pay for the underlying EC2 instances


Auto scaling group overall in AWS ? 

Minimum capacity - smallest number of instances running even during low demand 

Desired capacity - the target number of instances you aim to have during normal conditions 

Maximum capacity - the largest number of instances allowed , preventing over scaling 

Scale out - add more instances when demand increases
Scale in   -  remove more instances when demand decreases 


Auto scaling group in AWS with a load balancer ?

User -> load balancer -> instances 

→   Auto scaling group just helps when an instance is not healthy or scaling is needed 
→   as ASG scales out / in the load balancer updates it’s target pool of instances / task ( container ) 


Auto scaling group attributes ?

When scaling those instances it’s important that they are configured correctly so we have a “Launch Template”

Launch template consists of : 
→  Amazon machine image (template / pre-configured snapshot of the EC2 config) + instance type (t2.micro/large etc )(memory /network optimsed ect) = same setup
→  EC2 user data (scripts )
→  Elastic block storage (EBS) - persistent storage for instances 
→  Security groups - virtual firewalls to control in/outbound traffic to EC2 instances 

→  SSH keys - securely connect to instances 
→ IAM roles for EC2 instances - in order to interact with other AWS services - so u dont store access keys in your code 
→  Network + subnets information - need to indictate which subnets and VPC these EC2’s will be created 
→  Load balancer information  - min /Max / initial capacity of instances 
→  scaling policies ( rules of scaling ) with traffic 


Auto scaling - cloud watch alarms & scaling ?

→   It is possible to have Auto Scaling Groups based on CloudWatch alarms 
- Alarm monitors ( CPU , other metrics etc ) 
- Based on the alarm Scale In / Out policies can be created (number of instances )


Auto scaling - scaling policies ?

→  Simple / step scaling - adds / removes instances based on metrics / threshold 

→  Target tracking - scales up/ down based on a target and aims to keep it there 

→  Predictive scaling - anticipate scaling needs based on demand usage pattern 
